\begin_layout Section
The NEO Population
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Asteroids, comets, and large meteoroids whose orbit intersects or nearly
 intersects Earth's are classified as Near-Earth Objects (NEOs).
 These objects are typically divided into three major categories based on
 their orbital elements: the Aten, Apollo, and Amor groups, which are collective
ly known as the AAA asteroids 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "shoemaker1979earth"

\end_inset

.
 Atens are defined as objects having a semimajor axis 
\begin_inset Formula $a<1.0$
\end_inset

 and an aphelion distance 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\geq0.983$
\end_inset

 (the perihelion distance of Earth).
 This classification means that Aten objects only sometimes cross the orbit
 of Earth.
 Apollos are defined to have an 
\begin_inset Formula $a\geq1.0$
\end_inset

 and a perhelion distance 
\begin_inset Formula $q\leq1.0167$
\end_inset

 (the aphelion distance of Earth).
 Amors are defined solely by their perhelion distance, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $1.1067\leq q\leq1.3$
\end_inset

, meaning they are near-Earth-crossers but do not currently qualify as Earth-cro
ssing asteroids.
 An NEO is considered a potentially hazardous object (PHO) if its minimum
 orbit intersection distance (MOID) is less than 0.05 AU and has an absolute
 magnitude of 22.0 or less 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "jpl2014NEO"

\end_inset

.
 Orbital perturbations may, naturally, change the classification of any
 particular NEO between these groups.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The orbital characteristics of NEOs generally mean that they stay as NEOs
 for at most a few million years, eventually crashing into the Sun or terrestria
l planets, or being flung out of the solar system.
 The fact that the number of NEOs has remained steady over the last 3 billion
 years suggests that there is a source of resupply for the population 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bottke2002overview"

\end_inset

.
 It is believed that main belt asteroids (MBAs) provide the bulk of NEO
 resupply, with Jupiter and Saturn resonances causing asteroids to move
 from main belt to NEO orbits.
 Smaller NEOs are likely collision fragments from MBAs, and exhibit younger
 (less-weathered) surfaces due to the difficulty of surviving further collisions
 or planetary ecounters 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "binzel2002physical"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The NEO population is of special interest planetary astronomers because
 of its proximity to Earth.
 NEOs with low inclination and low eccentricity in particular are some of
 the best solar system targets for space missions due to the relatively
 low 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V$
\end_inset

 and short time frame required to reach them.
 Additionally, the inner solar system orbits and periodic proximity to Earth
 of these NEOs mean that thermal and power considerations for rendezvous
 and flyby missions can be significantly simplified compared to near-Sun
 or outer solar system missions, making them relatively low-cost and within
 the reach of early private-sector space missions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "perozzi2001basic"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

